# 2 Results for small orders 

It is well known [11] that there is a unique $\operatorname{KTS}(9)$ up to isomorphism, shown by the following triples on the point set $\{1,2, \ldots, 9\}$.

$$
\begin{array}{lll}
\{1,2,3\} & \{1,4,7\} & \{1,5,9\} & \{1,6,8\} \\
\{4,5,6\} & \{2,5,8\} & \{2,6,7\} & \{2,4,9\} \\
\{7,8,9\} & \{3,6,9\} & \{3,4,8\} & \{3,5,7\}
\end{array}
$$

Lemma 2.1. There exist 3-colourings of $\operatorname{KTS}(9)$ for each of the following colour types: $3^{3}$, $2^{1} 3^{1} 4^{1}$ and $1^{1} 4^{2}$.

Proof. Using the representation of the $\operatorname{KTS}(9)$ above, a 3 -colouring with colour type $3^{3}$ is given by the colour classes $\{1,4,9\},\{2,5,7\}$ and $\{3,6,8\}$; this is a rainbow colouring for which the parallel class containing the block $\{1,2,3\}$ is rainbow. For colour type $2^{1} 3^{1} 4^{1}$, consider the classes $\{1,2\},\{3,5,8\}$ and $\{4,6,7,9\}$. For colour type $1^{1} 4^{2}$, consider the classes $\{1\},\{2,3,5,9\}$ and $\{4,6,7,8\}$.

Now, for several small orders we explicitly provide rainbow colourings that will be useful in subsequent constructions.

Lemma 2.2. There exists a rainbow $\operatorname{KTS}(v)$ for each $v \in\{3,9,15,21,33,39,57,69\}$.
Proof. The result is clearly true for $v=3$, and for $v=9$ a rainbow colouring appears in the proof of Lemma 2.1. For $v=15$, the following $\operatorname{KTS}(15)$ (taken from Example 5.1.1 in [23]) has a rainbow colouring under the point partition $\{1,4,7,13,14\},\{2,5,6,8,9\}$ and $\{3,10,11,12,15\}$.

![table_0](table_0)

For $v \in\{21,33,39,57,69\}$ we constructed several $\operatorname{KTS}(v)$ in a manner similar to that described in [10], and in so doing we were able to identify several systems with rainbow colourings. The general approach here is to construct a $\operatorname{KTS}(v)$ on the point set $\left\{i_{j} \mid i \in \mathbb{Z}_{(v-3) / 3}, j \in \mathbb{Z}_{3}\right\} \cup\left\{\infty_{0}, \infty_{1}, \infty_{2}\right\}$ such that the permutation

$$
\sigma=\left(0_{0}, 1_{0}, \ldots,\left(\frac{v-6}{3}\right)_{0}\right)\left(0_{1}, 1_{1}, \ldots,\left(\frac{v-6}{3}\right)_{1}\right)\left(0_{2}, 1_{2}, \ldots,\left(\frac{v-6}{3}\right)_{2}\right)\left(\infty_{0}\right)\left(\infty_{1}\right)\left(\infty_{2}\right)
$$

fixes one parallel class, induces a short orbit of $\frac{v-3}{6}$ parallel classes and induces a long orbit of $\frac{v-3}{3}$ parallel classes. By assigning colour $j$ to each point $i_{j}$ where $i \in \mathbb{Z}_{(v-3) / 3} \cup\{\infty\}$, we will obtain a 3 -colouring for which the parallel class fixed by $\sigma$ is rainbow.

For $v=21$, the fixed parallel class contains the block $\left\{\infty_{0}, \infty_{1}, \infty_{2}\right\}$ as well as the development of the starter block $\left\{0_{0}, 4_{1}, 1_{2}\right\}$. The short orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having the blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{1_{0}, 1_{1}, 2_{1}\right\},\left\{2_{0}, 1_{2}, 2_{2}\right\}, \sigma^{3}\left(\left\{1_{0}, 1_{1}, 2_{1}\right\}\right), \sigma^{3}\left(\left\{2_{0}, 1_{2}, 2_{2}\right\}\right) \\
\left\{\infty_{0}, 0_{2}, 3_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{1}, 0_{0}, 3_{0}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 0_{1}, 3_{1}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

The long orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{0_{0}, 1_{0}, 3_{1}\right\},\left\{2_{0}, 4_{0}, 0_{2}\right\},\left\{1_{1}, 5_{1}, 3_{2}\right\},\left\{0_{1}, 1_{2}, 5_{2}\right\} \\
\left\{\infty_{1}, 4_{1}, 4_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 5_{0}, 2_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{0}, 3_{0}, 2_{1}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

For $v=33$, the fixed parallel class contains the block $\left\{\infty_{0}, \infty_{1}, \infty_{2}\right\}$ as well as the development of the starter block $\left\{0_{0}, 5_{1}, 2_{2}\right\}$. The short orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having the blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{1_{0}, 2_{0}, 1_{2}\right\},\left\{3_{0}, 1_{1}, 2_{1}\right\},\left\{4_{0}, 2_{2}, 8_{2}\right\},\left\{3_{1}, 9_{1}, 4_{2}\right\} \\
\sigma^{5}\left(\left\{1_{0}, 2_{0}, 1_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{5}\left(\left\{3_{0}, 1_{1}, 2_{1}\right\}\right), \sigma^{5}\left(\left\{4_{0}, 2_{2}, 8_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{5}\left(\left\{3_{1}, 9_{1}, 4_{2}\right\}\right) \\
\left\{\infty_{1}, 0_{0}, 5_{0}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 0_{1}, 5_{1}\right\},\left\{\infty_{0}, 0_{2}, 5_{2}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

The long orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{0_{0}, 2_{0}, 2_{1}\right\},\left\{1_{0}, 4_{0}, 7_{1}\right\},\left\{3_{0}, 7_{0}, 4_{1}\right\},\left\{5_{0}, 6_{2}, 8_{2}\right\},\left\{8_{0}, 4_{2}, 5_{2}\right\},\left\{0_{1}, 8_{1}, 2_{2}\right\} \\
\left\{6_{1}, 9_{1}, 9_{2}\right\},\left\{1_{1}, 0_{2}, 7_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{1}, 5_{1}, 3_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 6_{0}, 1_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{0}, 9_{0}, 3_{1}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

For $v=39$, the fixed parallel class contains the block $\left\{\infty_{0}, \infty_{1}, \infty_{2}\right\}$ plus the development of the starter block $\left\{0_{0}, 9_{1}, 3_{2}\right\}$. The short orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{1_{0}, 2_{0}, 1_{1}\right\},\left\{3_{0}, 4_{1}, 5_{1}\right\},\left\{4_{0}, 1_{2}, 2_{2}\right\},\left\{5_{0}, 4_{2}, 9_{2}\right\},\left\{2_{1}, 9_{1}, 5_{2}\right\} \\
\sigma^{6}\left(\left\{1_{0}, 2_{0}, 1_{1}\right\}\right), \sigma^{6}\left(\left\{3_{0}, 4_{1}, 5_{1}\right\}\right), \sigma^{6}\left(\left\{4_{0}, 1_{2}, 2_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{6}\left(\left\{5_{0}, 4_{2}, 9_{2}\right\}\right) \\
\sigma^{6}\left(\left\{2_{1}, 9_{1}, 5_{2}\right\}\right),\left\{\infty_{1}, 0_{0}, 6_{0}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 0_{1}, 6_{1}\right\},\left\{\infty_{0}, 0_{2}, 6_{2}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

The long orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{0_{0}, 2_{0}, 5_{1}\right\},\left\{1_{0}, 4_{0}, 8_{1}\right\},\left\{3_{0}, 7_{0}, 1_{1}\right\},\left\{5_{0}, 10_{0}, 0_{2}\right\},\left\{6_{0}, 7_{2}, 11_{2}\right\},\left\{9_{0}, 3_{2}, 5_{2}\right\},\left\{0_{1}, 9_{1}, 2_{2}\right\} \\
\left\{2_{1}, 4_{1}, 1_{2}\right\},\left\{6_{1}, 10_{1}, 10_{2}\right\},\left\{11_{1}, 6_{2}, 9_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{1}, 3_{1}, 4_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 8_{0}, 8_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{0}, 11_{0}, 7_{1}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

For $v=57$, the fixed parallel class contains the block $\left\{\infty_{0}, \infty_{1}, \infty_{2}\right\}$ plus the development of the starter block $\left\{0_{0}, 9_{1}, 10_{2}\right\}$. The short orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{1_{0}, 2_{0}, 1_{1}\right\},\left\{3_{0}, 5_{0}, 1_{2}\right\},\left\{4_{0}, 2_{1}, 5_{1}\right\},\left\{6_{0}, 3_{1}, 8_{1}\right\},\left\{7_{0}, 2_{2}, 4_{2}\right\},\left\{8_{0}, 7_{2}, 8_{2}\right\},\left\{6_{1}, 7_{1}, 3_{2}\right\} \\
\left\{1 3_{1}, 5_{2}, 15_{2}\right\}, \sigma^{9}\left(\left\{1_{0}, 2_{0}, 1_{1}\right\}\right), \sigma^{9}\left(\left\{3_{0}, 5_{0}, 1_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{9}\left(\left\{4_{0}, 2_{1}, 5_{1}\right\}\right), \sigma^{9}\left(\left\{6_{0}, 3_{1}, 8_{1}\right\}\right) \\
\sigma^{9}\left(\left\{7_{0}, 2_{2}, 4_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{9}\left(\left\{8_{0}, 7_{2}, 8_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{9}\left(\left\{6_{1}, 7_{1}, 3_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{9}\left(\left\{1 3_{1}, 5_{2}, 15_{2}\right\}\right),\left\{\infty_{1}, 0_{0}, 9_{0}\right\} \\
\left\{\infty_{2}, 0_{1}, 9_{1}\right\},\left\{\infty_{0}, 0_{2}, 9_{2}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

The long orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{0_{0}, 3_{0}, 6_{1}\right\},\left\{1_{0}, 5_{0}, 9_{1}\right\},\left\{2_{0}, 8_{0}, 15_{1}\right\},\left\{4_{0}, 11_{0}, 13_{2}\right\},\left\{6_{0}, 16_{0}, 9_{2}\right\},\left\{12_{0}, 17_{0}, 6_{2}\right\},\left\{7_{0}, 0_{1}, 12_{1}\right\} \\
\left\{9_{0}, 1_{1}, 3_{1}\right\},\left\{13_{0}, 1_{2}, 14_{2}\right\},\left\{14_{0}, 0_{2}, 4_{2}\right\},\left\{7_{1}, 14_{1}, 7_{2}\right\},\left\{8_{1}, 16_{1}, 2_{2}\right\},\left\{13_{1}, 17_{1}, 16_{2}\right\} \\
\left\{2_{1}, 8_{2}, 11_{2}\right\},\left\{5_{1}, 3_{2}, 10_{2}\right\},\left\{10_{1}, 5_{2}, 17_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{1}, 4_{1}, 12_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 10_{0}, 15_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{0}, 15_{0}, 11_{1}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

For $v=69$, the fixed parallel class contains the block $\left\{\infty_{0}, \infty_{1}, \infty_{2}\right\}$ plus the development of the starter block $\left\{0_{0}, 14_{1}, 9_{2}\right\}$. The short orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{1_{0}, 2_{0}, 1_{1}\right\},\left\{3_{0}, 5_{0}, 6_{1}\right\},\left\{4_{0}, 7_{0}, 1_{2}\right\},\left\{6_{0}, 2_{1}, 3_{1}\right\},\left\{8_{0}, 3_{2}, 4_{2}\right\},\left\{9_{0}, 2_{2}, 7_{2}\right\},\left\{10_{0}, 9_{2}, 16_{2}\right\}, \\
\left\{9_{1}, 15_{1}, 6_{2}\right\},\left\{10_{1}, 18_{1}, 8_{2}\right\},\left\{16_{1}, 19_{1}, 21_{2}\right\}, \sigma^{11}\left(\left\{1_{0}, 2_{0}, 1_{1}\right\}\right), \sigma^{11}\left(\left\{3_{0}, 5_{0}, 6_{1}\right\}\right), \\
\sigma^{11}\left(\left\{4_{0}, 7_{0}, 1_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{11}\left(\left\{6_{0}, 2_{1}, 3_{1}\right\}\right), \sigma^{11}\left(\left\{8_{0}, 3_{2}, 4_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{11}\left(\left\{9_{0}, 2_{2}, 7_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{11}\left(\left\{10_{0}, 9_{2}, 16_{2}\right\}\right), \\
\sigma^{11}\left(\left\{9_{1}, 15_{1}, 6_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{11}\left(\left\{10_{1}, 18_{1}, 8_{2}\right\}\right), \sigma^{11}\left(\left\{16_{1}, 19_{1}, 21_{2}\right\}\right),\left\{\infty_{1}, 0_{0}, 11_{0}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 0_{1}, 11_{1}\right\}, \\
\left\{\infty_{0}, 0_{2}, 11_{2}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

The long orbit of parallel classes is generated from a parallel class having blocks

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left\{0_{0}, 4_{0}, 2_{1}\right\},\left\{1_{0}, 6_{0}, 10_{1}\right\},\left\{3_{0}, 9_{0}, 14_{1}\right\},\left\{5_{0}, 20_{0}, 15_{1}\right\},\left\{7_{0}, 17_{0}, 8_{2}\right\},\left\{11_{0}, 19_{0}, 19_{2}\right\}, \\
\left\{12_{0}, 21_{0}, 1_{2}\right\},\left\{14_{0}, 4_{1}, 8_{1}\right\},\left\{15_{0}, 1_{1}, 6_{1}\right\},\left\{16_{0}, 0_{1}, 9_{1}\right\},\left\{8_{0}, 13_{2}, 15_{2}\right\},\left\{10_{0}, 2_{2}, 14_{2}\right\}, \\
\left\{13_{0}, 3_{2}, 16_{2}\right\},\left\{11_{1}, 21_{1}, 7_{2}\right\},\left\{13_{1}, 20_{1}, 20_{2}\right\},\left\{17_{1}, 19_{1}, 11_{2}\right\},\left\{5_{1}, 6_{2}, 9_{2}\right\},\left\{7_{1}, 10_{2}, 18_{2}\right\}, \\
\left\{12_{1}, 5_{2}, 21_{2}\right\},\left\{16_{1}, 0_{2}, 4_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{1}, 18_{1}, 17_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{2}, 2_{0}, 12_{2}\right\},\left\{\infty_{0}, 18_{0}, 3_{1}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

We will discuss rainbow colourings in more detail in Section 3, but we pause here to briefly note that the several preceding instances of 3 -chromatic Kirkman triple systems can be used to generate further examples of 3 -chromatic Kirkman triple systems.
Theorem 2.3. Let $v \geqslant 3$. Suppose that there exists a $\operatorname{KTS}(3 v)$ which has a 3-colouring that is equitable. Then there exists a $\operatorname{KTS}(9 v)$ which has a 3-colouring that is equitable.
Proof. Let $A_{1}=\left\{a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{v}\right\}, A_{2}=\left\{a_{v+1}, a_{v+2}, \ldots, a_{2 v}\right\}$ and $A_{3}=\left\{a_{2 v+1}, a_{2 v+2}, \ldots, a_{3 v}\right\}$, with $B_{1}, B_{2}, B_{3}, C_{1}, C_{2}$ and $C_{3}$ similarly defined. Next, let $A=A_{1} \cup A_{2} \cup A_{3}$ with $B$ and $C$ similarly defined.

We construct a $\operatorname{KTS}(9 v)=(A \cup B \cup C, \mathcal{B})$ as follows. Add to $\mathcal{B}$ the blocks of a 3 -coloured $\operatorname{KTS}(3 v)$ on each of $A, B$ and $C$ in such a way that the vertices in the set $A_{i} \cup B_{i} \cup C_{i}$ have colour $i$, for each $1 \leqslant i \leqslant 3$.

Necessarily $v$ is odd; otherwise a $\operatorname{KTS}(3 v)$ does not exist. Thus there exists a Latin square $L_{v}$ of order $v$ which partitions into transversals $T_{1}, T_{2}, \ldots, T_{v}$. Equivalently, there is a 3 -RGDD of type $v^{3}$ (a resolvable transversal design), $G$. Add to $\mathcal{B}$ nine copies of $G$, using the following sets of three groups:

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\left\{A_{1}, B_{1}, C_{2}\right\}, & \left\{A_{2}, B_{2}, C_{3}\right\}, \quad\left\{A_{3}, B_{3}, C_{1}\right\} \\
\left\{A_{1}, B_{2}, C_{1}\right\}, & \left\{A_{2}, B_{3}, C_{2}\right\}, \quad\left\{A_{3}, B_{1}, C_{3}\right\} \\
\left\{A_{1}, B_{3}, C_{3}\right\}, & \left\{A_{2}, B_{1}, C_{1}\right\}, \quad\left\{A_{3}, B_{2}, C_{2}\right\}
\end{array}
$$

To see that the added blocks can be partitioned into parallel classes, let

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{X}_{1}=\left(\left\{A_{1}, B_{1}, C_{2}\right\},\left\{A_{2}, B_{2}, C_{3}\right\},\left\{A_{3}, B_{3}, C_{1}\right\}\right) \\
& \mathcal{X}_{2}=\left(\left\{A_{1}, B_{2}, C_{1}\right\},\left\{A_{2}, B_{3}, C_{2}\right\},\left\{A_{3}, B_{1}, C_{3}\right\}\right) \\
& \mathcal{X}_{3}=\left(\left\{A_{1}, B_{3}, C_{3}\right\},\left\{A_{2}, B_{1}, C_{1}\right\},\left\{A_{3}, B_{2}, C_{2}\right\}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

and let $G_{i, j, k}$ be the $k^{\text {th }}$ parallel class in the copy of $G$ placed on the $j^{\text {th }}$ set of groups in $\mathcal{X}_{i}$. For each $i \in\{1,2,3\}$ and $k \in\{1, \ldots, v\}, G_{i, 1, k} \cup G_{i, 2, k} \cup G_{i, 3, k}$ forms a parallel class.

In addition to the Kirkman triple systems produced by Theorem 2.3, we call attention to the family of Kirkman triple systems that arise from the Bose construction. Resolvable Bose triple systems are studied in [25], where it is shown that for such a triple system to exist it must have order $v \equiv 9(\bmod 18)$. Moreover, for each $v \equiv 9(\bmod 18)$ such a system is constructed. The resolvable Bose triple systems that are constructed in [25] are observed to all have equitable 3 -colourings.

We finish this section with some comments on small Kirkman triple systems that are not 3 -chromatic. In [33], Tonchev and Vanstone presented thirty non-isomorphic KTS(33). We analysed each of them computationally by implementing an exhaustive backtracking algorithm to search for potential colourings. In so doing we found that none of them can be 3 -coloured, but they each admit a 4 -colouring that is equitable and of type $8^{3} 9^{1}$; we include an appendix with details of such colourings. Additionally, we tested the 1-rotational $\operatorname{KTS}(33)$ over the cyclic group given by Buratti and Zuanni [5], and found that 13 are 3 chromatic, while the rest are all 4 -chromatic; we give an example of one of the 3 -chromatic systems from [5] in the appendix. We also tested the 3 -pyramidal KTS(33) from [2] and found that it was 4 -chromatic. It seems that, at least in the case $v=33$, a high degree of symmetry correlates with a higher chromatic number.

Lastly we observe that sporadic examples of Kirkman triple systems with chromatic number greater than 4 appear in the literature. Fugère, Haddad and Wehlau [14] prove that the points and lines of the projective geometry $\mathrm{PG}(5,2)$ form a 5 -chromatic Steiner triple system; it is known that $\mathrm{PG}(n, 2)$ is resolvable whenever $n$ is odd [1], so that this design yields a 5 -chromatic KTS(63). In [17], Haddad shows that the Steiner triple system derived from the affine geometry $\mathrm{AG}(4,3)$ is 5 -chromatic; it follows that there exists a $\operatorname{KTS}(81)$ which is 5 -chromatic. Bruen, Haddad and Wehlau [4] show that the KTS(243) given by the affine geometry $\mathrm{AG}(5,3)$ is 6 -chromatic.
